1190","1143":"1143","1164":"1164","1120":"1120","1142":"1142","1141":"1141","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1171":"1171","1170":"1170","um 1171":"about 1171","ABT 1195":"about 1195","um 1170":"about 1170","<1169>":"1169","1169":"1169","um 1141":"about 1141","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","1210":"1210","um 1167":"about 1167","1229":"1229","Deutschland":"Germany","<Of, Peggau, Steiermark, Austria>":"Peggau, Graz Umgebung, Styria, Austria","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Lebenau","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Normand, Andre, Pierre, Fernand, Gaston, Solange, Adelard, Baptiste, Cecile, Chantel, Donat.","French: nickname from <i>le beau</i> ‘the handsome’, a variant of   Beau   1, with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>. It is also found in England, as a surname of Huguenot origin. See also   Lebel  .","Altered form, with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>, of French   Bau  . Compare   Labeau  ,   Labo  ,   Lebo  , and   Lebow  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lebo","meanings":["Altered form of French   Lebeau   1 and French Canadian   Lebeau   2. Compare   Lebow  .","Hungarian (<b>Lebó</b>): unexplained. It is also found in Slovakia.","Croatian: unexplained."]},{"name":"Labo","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Lebeau   1 or French Canadian   Lebeau   2."]},{"name":"Beau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Laurent, Pascal, Remi.","French: nickname for a handsome man (perhaps also ironically for an ugly one), from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘beautiful, handsome’ (from Late Latin <i>bellus</i>). This surname is also found in Germany. Compare   Bel   and   Lebeau  ."]},{"name":"Labeau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Amiee, Phillippe, Pierre.","Altered form of French   Lebeau   1 ‘the handsome’ and French Canadian   Lebeau   2, with the feminine definite article <i>la</i> instead of masculine <i>le</i> (a change that may have also been the result of the American English pronunciation).","In some cases possibly also French: topographic name derived from Latin <i>albellus</i> ‘white poplar’, with fused definite article <i>l'</i>; or perhaps a variant of <b>Abeau</b>, itself a very rare variant of the personal name   Abel  ."]},{"name":"Lebow","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Lebeau   1 or French Canadian   Lebeau   2, or of their altered form   Lebo   1."]}]},{"name":"Otto","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a short form of any of the various Germanic compound personal names containing the element <i>od</i>, <i>ot</i> ‘prosperity, wealth’ (  compare the corresponding Old English <i>ēad</i> in names such as  Edward   and   Edwin  ).  St Otto of Bamberg  (  d. 1139 ) was a missionary to the Pomeranians.  Otto the Great  (  912–73 ) is generally regarded as the founder of the Holy Roman Empire, and the name has been borne by several members of German and Austrian royal houses. It was recorded occasionally among immigrants to England from the Low Countries in the 14th century, but failed to establish itself. Since the 19th century it has again been used occasionally in the English-speaking world, mostly among immigrants from Germanic countries."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Otto von Lebenau was born about 1141, in Germany, his father, Siegf